# 📍 Day 11 — Decoupling (SQS, SNS, Kinesis, MQ)

## 🎯 Objective

Understand how AWS services help decouple applications for scalability and reliability.

---

## 🔗 What is Decoupling?

* Breaking tight dependencies between services
* Allows independent scaling and failure handling

---

## 📩 SQS (Simple Queue Service)

### 📌 Key Features

* Message queue
* Decouples producer & consumer
* Supports:

  * Standard Queue (high throughput)
  * FIFO Queue (ordered, no duplicates)

---

## 📢 SNS (Simple Notification Service)

### 📌 Key Features

* Pub/Sub messaging
* Sends messages to multiple subscribers
* Can trigger:

  * SQS
  * Lambda
  * Email/SMS

---

## 📊 Kinesis

### 📌 Key Features

* Real-time data streaming
* Handles large-scale data ingestion
* Used for analytics pipelines

---

## 🔌 Amazon MQ

### 📌 Key Features

* Managed message broker
* Supports ActiveMQ / RabbitMQ
* Useful for migrating legacy systems

---

## ⚖️ Comparison

| Service | Use Case               |
| ------- | ---------------------- |
| SQS     | Queue-based decoupling |
| SNS     | Pub/Sub notifications  |
| Kinesis | Real-time streaming    |
| MQ      | Legacy messaging       |

---

## 💡 Key Learnings

* Decoupling improves scalability & fault tolerance
* SQS + SNS combination is very common
* Kinesis is used for real-time big data

---

## 🚧 Challenges Faced

* Understanding differences between SQS vs SNS
* When to use Kinesis vs SQS

